{"title_page": "Presiding Officer of the Scottish Parliament", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post            = Presiding Officer\n|body            = [[Scottish Parliament|the Scottish Parliament]]\n|member_of       = [[Scottish Parliamentary Corporate Body]]\n|insignia        = \n|insigniasize    = 200px\n|image           = KenMacintoshMSP20110511.jpg\n|imagesize       = 175px\n|incumbent       = [[Ken Macintosh]]\n|incumbentsince  = 12 May 2016\n|style           = Presiding Officer<br /><small>(Within Parliament)</small><br />The [[Right Honourable]]<br /><small>(Formal)</small>\n|termlength      = Elected by the Scottish Parliament at the start of each session, and upon a vacancy\n|formation       = 1999\n|succession      =\n|deputy          = Deputy Presiding Officers\n|salary          = {{currency|106,290|GBP}}\n|inaugural       = [[David Steel]]\n|website         = {{url|https://www.parliament.scot/abouttheparliament/presiding-officer.aspx}}\n}}\n{{Politics of Scotland}}\nThe '''Presiding Officer of the Scottish Parliament''' ({{lang-gd|Oifigear-Riaghlaidh}}, {{lang-sco|Preses o the Scots Pairlament}}) is the [[speaker (politics)|speaker]] of the [[Scottish Parliament]].  They are [[Members of the Scottish Parliament|Member of the Scottish Parliament]] elected by the Scottish Parliament by means of an [[exhaustive ballot]], and is ''ex officio'' the head of the [[Scottish Parliamentary Corporate Body]].  He is considered a figurehead of the Scottish Parliament and holds an office in [[Queensberry House]].\n\nThe office of the Presiding Officer was established by an act of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]], the [[Scotland Act 1998]]. The current Presiding Officer is [[Ken Macintosh]], who was elected on 12 May 2016, following the [[2016 Scottish Parliament election]].\n\n==Office==\nThe Presiding Officer presides over the Parliament's debates, determining which members may speak, and maintains order during debate.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/6651101.stm |title=Q&A: Holyrood presiding officer |first=Andrew |last=Black |work=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=14 May 2007}}</ref> The Presiding Officer is expected to be strictly non-partisan, with some similarities in this respect to the tradition of the [[Speaker of the British House of Commons]]. For this reason, they renounce all affiliation with their former political party for the duration of their term.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.holyrood.com/articles/inside-politics/former-scottish-parliament-presiding-officers-devolution-years |title=Former Scottish Parliament Presiding Officers on the devolution years |work=[[Holyrood (magazine)|Holyrood]] |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=26 February 2017}}</ref> They do not take part in debate, or vote except to break ties.  Even then, the convention is that when the Presiding Officer uses their tie-breaking vote, they do so in favour of the status quo. The Presiding Officer is also assisted in their duties by 2 deputies. They have the same powers as the Presiding Officer but they keep their party affiliation but remain impartial when presiding.\n\nIn 2006 the St Andrews Fund for Scots Heraldry commemorated the hosting of the [[International Congress of Genealogical and Heraldic Sciences|Heraldic & Genealogical Congress]] in Scotland by commissioning a ceremonial robe for the Presiding Officer to wear, however as of May 2017, it appears no Presiding Officer has worn the robe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.andrewcusack.com/2010/presiding-officers-gown/|title=The Presiding Officer\u2019s Gown  {{!}}  andrewcusack.com|last=Cusack|first=Andrew|date=3 June 2010|website=www.andrewcusack.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=12 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Scottish National Party]] proposes that in the event of [[Scottish independence|independence]], the Presiding Officer's post be replaced with that of [[Lord Chancellor of Scotland|Chancellor of Scotland]]. In addition to presiding over the Scottish Parliament, the Chancellor would possess additional constitutional powers during the absence of the Monarch from Scotland; chiefly, the Chancellor should act in a role similar to a [[Governor-General]] in the other [[Commonwealth realm]]s.<ref>\n[http://www.constitutionalcommission.org/production/byre/images/assets/Principles%20of%20the%20Constitution.pdf ''Principles of the Constitution''], at constitutionalcommission.org (.pdf file)</ref>\n\n==List of Presiding Officers==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \"\n|- style=\"text-align: center; background: #efefef; border-bottom: 2px solid gray;\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|\n!Name\n!Entered office\n!Left office\n!Former party\n!Constituency / Region\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Liberal Democrats}}|\n|1.\n|Sir [[David Steel]]{{efn|Officially styled as The Lord Steel of Aikwood, but he was known as Sir David Steel in the Scottish Parliament.}}\n|12 May 1999\n|7 May 2003\n|[[Scottish Liberal Democrats|Liberal Democrats]]\n|[[Lothians (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Lothians]]\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|2.\n| [[George Reid (Scottish politician)|George Reid]]\n|7 May 2003\n|14 May 2007\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Ochil (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Ochil]]\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Conservative Party}}|\n|3.\n| [[Alex Fergusson (politician)|Alex Fergusson]]\n|14 May 2007\n|11 May 2011\n|[[Scottish Conservative Party|Conservative]]\n|[[Galloway and Upper Nithsdale (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Galloway and Upper Nithsdale]]\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}}|\n|4.\n|[[Tricia Marwick]]\n|11 May 2011\n|12 May 2016\n|[[Scottish National Party]]\n|[[Mid Fife and Glenrothes (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Mid Fife and Glenrothes]]\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|5.\n|[[Ken Macintosh]]\n|12 May 2016\n|Incumbent\n|[[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]]\n|[[West Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|West Scotland]]\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==List of Deputy Presiding Officers==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"6\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 0 0 0 1em; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaaaaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; \"\n|- style=\"text-align: center; background: #efefef; border-bottom: 2px solid gray;\"\n!colspan=\"1\"|\n!Name\n!Party\n!Constituency / Region\n!colspan=\"1\"|\n!Name\n!Party\n!Constituency / Region\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}}|\n|[[Patricia Ferguson]] <small>12 May 1999 \u2013 27 November 2001</small>\n|[[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]]\n|[[Glasgow Maryhill (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Glasgow Maryhill]]\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish National Party}} rowspan=\"2\"|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[George Reid (Scottish politician)|George Reid]]<br /><small>12 May 1999-7 May2003</small>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish National Party|SNP]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Mid Scotland and Fife (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|Mid Scotland and Fife]]\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Conservative Party}} rowspan=\"2\"|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Murray Tosh]] <small>29 November 2001 \u2013 2 April 2007</small>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Scottish Conservative Party|Conservative]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[South of Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|South of Scotland]] {{small|(1999-2003)}}<br /> [[West of Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|West of Scotland]] {{small|(2003-2007)}}\n|-\n|{{Scottish politics/party colours/Scottish Labour Party}} rowspan=\"3\"|\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Trish Godman]]<br /><small>7 May 2003 \u2013 22 March 2011</small>\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Scottish Labour Party|Labour]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[West Renfrewshire (Scottish Parliament constituency